<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="768">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182089" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tristicula Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tristicula Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristicula">tristicula</taxonomicName>
, dim. of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34070" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tristis (Smith)" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tristis (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristis">tristis</taxonomicName>
, sad.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="768">
Diagnosis A small, bicolorous, mostly yellow species belonging to a group of ambiguous species composing the &quot; 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33648" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole carapuna Mann" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole carapuna Mann" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carapuna">carapuna</taxonomicName>
complex&quot; (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182016" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole boltoni Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole boltoni Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boltoni">boltoni</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33648" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole carapuna Mann" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole carapuna Mann" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carapuna">carapuna</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182023" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole cornicula Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole cornicula Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornicula">cornicula</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182025" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole cuprina Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole cuprina Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuprina">cuprina</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182029" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole eriophora Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole eriophora Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eriophora">eriophora</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182048" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole jivaro Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole jivaro Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jivaro">jivaro</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182052" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole manuana Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole manuana Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manuana">manuana</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182089" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tristicula Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tristicula Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristicula">tristicula</taxonomicName>
). All are relatively small in size, with the major possessing a reduced mesonotal convexity and cephalic sculpturing that consists entirely of longitudinal carinulae that extend to or almost to the occipital border seen in full-face view. All also have a minor with a broad, concave occiput, which lacks a collar. Among these species, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182089" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tristicula Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tristicula Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristicula">P. tristicula</taxonomicName>
is distinguished in the major by combination of its elevated humerus in dorsal-oblique view, laterally angular postpetiolar node, transversely carinulate pronotal dorsum, partially shagreened first gastral tergite, and in color. It is closest to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33648" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole carapuna Mann" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole carapuna Mann" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="768" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carapuna">carapuna</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="768">Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 1.08, HL 1.24, SL 0.64, EL 0.18, PW 0.60. Paratype minor: HW 0.56, HL 0.60, SL 0.54, EL 0.12, PW 0.38.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="768">Color Major and minor: head and mesosoma light reddish yellow (&quot;orange&quot;), rest of body and appendages clear medium yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="768">range A very widespread but overall not abundant species. I have identified series from Veracruz, Mexico; Honduras; Colombia; French Guiana; Trinidad; and scattered localities in Amazonian Brazil, Ecuador, Peru, and Bolivia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="768">biology At Cuzco Amazonico, near Puerto Maldonado, Peru, Stefan Cover and John E. Tobin found a colony in mature rainforest, nesting in humus on top of a rotten log. Similarly, Mark Moffett collected a colony from a rotten log at Saul, French Guiana.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
